general than this derivation might suggest. A proof can be easily constructed for an arbitrary internal correlation function (not necessarily of the form given in eq 39) as long as the three conditions stated above hold.

In the above development, we have assumed that all the internal

motions are faster than the overall motion (i.e., , « for all

;). What happens if some component of the internal correlation

function decays more slowly than the overall motion? Suppose,

for example, that in eq 39 , »

