of extensive numerical experimentation, we conjecture that if eq 61 holds to within ~2%, this is indeed the case. Motions of this nature will be called extremely fast internal motions. In the case of extremely fast motions, eq 61 is virtually exact and P2 and re can be determined very accurately by using the analytical expressions 59a and 59b for 7) data at two fields or eq 60a and 60b for Tx and NOE data at one field. For example, for 13C-‘H dipolar relaxation with = 10~8, at a 13C resonance frequency of ~90.5 MHz, internal motions such that re 5 50 ps fall in this category. Table III illustrates an example of extremely fast internal motions for Woessner’s diffusional model. Exact data
were generated for = 10“8 s, ß = 70.5°, and 1/6D = 10.6 ps. Fitting only Tx and NOE at high field, we can extract cP2 and re almost exactly and predict very accurately the other relaxation data. For these fast internal motions, one can use simple analytical formulas to extract <P2 and re from a set of two relaxation data, e.g., 7j and NOE at 90.5 MHz. Using eq 60a and 60b with (Tx)0 = 461 ms, NOE0 = 1.16, one obtains P2 = 0.114, re = 31.1 ps (with an error of less than 1%); using eq 37 with (T2)0 = 22.6 ms, one predicts T2 = 178 ms at 90.5 MHz (exact value 182 ms). For the relaxation parameters at low field, using eq 37 for Tx and
T2 and eq 38 for the NOE with (7j)0 = 46.6 ms, ( 2)0 = 18.1
ms, and NOE0 = 1.21, one predicts Tx = 332 ms (exact value 335 ms), T2 = 146 ms (exact value 149 ms), and NOE = 1.55
(exact value 1.51).
It is of some interest that, in the limit of extremely fast internal
motions, the spectral density at nonzero frequencies is fairly insensitive to large percent variations of P2 when P2 is very small, say 50.005, whereas the zero-frequency term depends strongly on P2, especially if rM is relatively slow. For example, if rM = 10“7 s, re = 19 ps, and P2 = 3 X 10"3, a change in P2 of 53% brings about a variation in Tx and NOE of less than 0.1%, whereas the T2 values change by 29%. However, given the physical interpretation of the generalized order parameter, it is uninteresting to determine P2 very accurately when it is that small. In general, for large amplitude motions, small changes in the allowed spatial range bring about a large percent change in the value of the generalized order parameter. For example, in the diffusion in a cone model, an order parameter of 3.0 X 10“3 corresponds to a cone angle of ~84°; P2 = 4.5 X 10'3 corresponds to a cone angle of ~83°. Thus, a variation of ~50% in the order parameter involves a change of only ~1% in the cone angle. Even for extremely fast motions, if P2 5 10'3, usually T2 information is required to extract the exact value of the order parameter. Thus, if one uses <P2 values extracted only from Tx and NOE data to predict T2 values when P2 is very small, the T2 values are likely
to be inaccurate.
We now present some examples of the model-free analysis of relaxation data when some of the internal motions are not fast
while others are in the extreme narrowing limit. To illustrate this point, let us consider the model of Brainard and Szabo6 for the motion of a carbon nonrigidly attached to a spherical macromolecule in such a way that the C-H vector can rotate freely about an axis d, which in turn is allowed to wobble within a cone of semiangle 0 about a director d attached to the macromolecule. The angle between the C-H vector and d is fixed at a value ß. The correlation time for the motion about d is T|¡, and t± is the

correlation time for the wobbling of the d axis. Exact NMR data were generated for ß = 70.5°, = 30°, rM = 10 ns, ± = 100 ns, and t¡| = 10 ps by using eq 15 of ref 6. The order parameter for this model is 0.072. For no motion of the d axis, P2 = 0.11.

Fitting Tx and NOE values at 25 and 90 MHz by using the

model-free approach, we obtained re = 30 ps and P2 = 0.11, which
correspond to no motion of d. Addition of T2 information gives virtually identical results. In this case, for one internal motion,

the slow internal motion is “invisible”. We then considered the

Brainard-Szabo model with all the parameters as in the above example except that r± was set at a value of 1 ns. Fitting Tx and NOE values at both fields, we obtained P2 = 0.089 and re = 40 ps. The addition of T2 information gives P2 = 0.079 and re =
41 ps. The effective correlation time appears to be fast, but the order parameter has a value that is intermediate between 0.11

(corresponding to rotation about the d axis only) and 0.072

(corresponding to rotation and wobbling).

We now turn to the case where all the internal motions are not

close to the extreme narrowing limit. In this case, both terms in

the model-free expression for the spectral density depend on frequency. It is important to realize that, in general, the correlation

function for internal motions is not accurately described by a single exponential. The consequences of the one-exponential approximation are particularly severe for motions that are not very restricted (small values of P2) or, irrespective of the spatial extent of the motions, if the time scale of the motions is slow. For

relatively slow motions, we observed that, with very few exceptions, the trend is to predict values of P2 that are too large and values of re that are too small.
Table IV shows the results obtained by using the model-free

approach to analyze 13C relaxation data generated by using

Woessner’s model14 for

= 10 ns, 1/6Z> = 99.3 ps, and ß =

70.5°. For these relatively slow internal motions, it is still possible

to extract fairly accurate values of P2 and re (in error by 25%

and 15%, respectively) from a set of Tx and NOE measurements

at two fields. The predicted values of T2 are in good agreement

with the exact values at both fields (with an error of 11% at high

field and of 7% at low field).

