Lipari and Szabo
be simulated if the parameters for the motion of the macromolecule are known from other experiments (e.g., hydrodynamic or light-scattering measurements). One has to determine A, r,,
and t2 in this fashion; subsequently, when data are interpreted for nuclei that have internal motions, the parameters for internal motions will be allowed to vary while A, rlf and t2 are held fixed.
Extensive numerical investigations showed that even in the case of the anisotropic motions, the internal motions can be adequately described by using the model-free approach. The accuracy of the predicted values of P2 and re depends on the time scale of the motion. However, the procedure used in determining the parameters for the overall motion introduces an additional error in
the approximate correlation functions, and the inclusion of T2 information may improve slightly the accuracy of the predicted values of P2 and rc. We will briefly summarize the results of our numerical investigations and then present some illustrative ex-
amples. The first case of interest is the one of extremely fast motions,
i.e., motions such that eq 61 is satisfied to within ~2%, where
now is defined as r~’ = 2_1 + ~ (recall that we assume that
tj and r2 are defined in such a way that r1 > r2). In this case, a set of measurements (e.g., NOE and 7,) at one field can give accurate values of P2 and re, and relaxation data at all other fields such that (4) is satisfied to within ~2% can be predicted accurately. For anisotropic overall motion, however, the inclusion of information at another field (e.g., 7, and NOE) does slightly improve the extracted values of P2 and re, probably due to the method employed in determining the parameters for the macromolecular motion. A simple general criterion to determine the accuracy of the predicted values of P2 for arbitrary values of r¡ and t2 does not seem to exist; however, we estimate that as long
as the overall motion is not too slow ( , < 0.1 ps), data at one
field should give P2 values accurate to within ~5%, with the accuracy improving for larger order parameters. For fast internal motions, i.e., motions such that eq 61 is satisfied to within ~10%, one can extract accurate values of P2 and re from a set of measurements (e.g., 7t and NOE) at two fields. Again, the situation is slightly worse than in the isotropic case. We estimate that as long as 2 < 0.1 ps, one can predict P2 with an error no larger than ~20%, with the error being substantially smaller for larger order parameters. By including T2 information, one obtains virtually exact answers.
Slower motions follow a pattern similar to the one observed in the isotropic case. For motions such that (o>re)2 á 1, one can obtain fairly accurate values of P2 from a set of measurements at both fields including T2 information. For large order parameters (P2 2; 0.4), one can obtain accurate values of P2 and re for motions on all time scales.
Table VIII describes results obtained for the diffusion in a cone
model superimposed to an overall anisotropic motion with 1 /6DX = 1 ps, 1/6D2 = 0.05 ps, and /3Md = 15°. Exact results were generated for 13C-’H dipolar relaxation at 25.1 and 90.5 MHz: for 0 = 66.4°, 1/6Z)w = 10.9, 56.4 and 97.6 ps. For the fastest motion (1 /6Z>W = 10.9 ps), we obtain an accurate prediction of both P2 and re just by fitting 7, and NOE at high field. The extracted P2 value is slightly improved by fitting NOE and T{ at both fields. For 1/67>W = 56.4 ps, using 7, and NOE at both fields, one obtains P2 = 0.116 (the exact value is 0.0784), re = 81.9 ps (the exact value is 79.8 ps). By including T2 information, one obtains P2 = 0.0783 and re = 78.9 ps. For the slowest motion (1/6£>w = 97.6 ps, re = 137 ps), one obtains P2 = 0.2041 and re = 155 ps by fitting just NOE and Tl at both fields; i.e., without including T2 information, the predicted value of the order parameter is about three times bigger than the exact value. The inclusion of T2 information, however, allows a very accurate prediction of both P2 and re that differs from their exact values by 0.1% and 1.5%, respectively.
